        {
            $this-&gt;user_id = $user_id;
        }
        
        /**
         * @return mixed
         */
        public function getUserId()
        {
            return $this-&gt;user_id;
        }
    }



Event Listener for that Event implements `ShouldQueue`, so it processed by queue.

On `EventListener@handle` method I query database with `    $user = User::find($event-&gt;getUserId());`

    class UserRegisteredListener implements ShouldQueue
    {
        /**
         * Create the event listener.
         *
         * @return void
         */
        public function __construct()
        {
            //
        }
    
        /**
         * Handle the event.
         *
         * @param  UserRegistered  $event
         * @return void
         */
        public function handle(UserRegistered $event)
        {
            $user = User::find($event-&gt;getUserId());
            
            if (is_null($user)) {
                Log::info($event-&gt;getUserId());
                Log::error(&quot;User not found&quot;);
                
                return;
            }
            
            // Some work
        }
    }


**The problem:**

Sometimes (one of 100/1000 i.e) `User::find` returns `null` instead of an record, but I&#39;m sure that such record exists in database!

User ID is ok, I&#39;m logging it to the log file right after this query, and its existing user id.

Any ideas why sometimes record not found in database (when its **exists**)?

**SOLUTION**

I finally found the solution:

I have `DB::beginTransaction` and `DB::commit` calls within registration service. Event was fired **BEFORE** `DB::commit` call, so it was a `race condition` for what will be first: `commit` or event.

